    {
      "id": "9e02ce7c8c80989540c956f939ec17115e8ec3ac",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-03-16 18:54:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nToro has started the test process",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b053a42f7ba8c1632cd0089e1c60c1f585ea3752",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-16 19:19:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThere should always be a symlink from the unversioned .so library to the latest versioned name.  Is the concern that libzfs.so.2 will not work with a compiled mkfs.lustre?\n\nThe converse problem would be introduced by this patch - that now the mkfs_lustre.c file needs to be modified depending on which version of libzfs is installed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4b8ad63bdc120fb613d54584152553304533e433",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 272,
        "name": "Alexey Shvetsov",
        "email": "alexxy@gentoo.org",
        "username": "alexxy"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-16 19:44:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThats not always true. Upstream seems installs only versioned symlink\n\nlustre ~ # ls -l /lib64/lib{zfs,nvpair}.so* \nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root     18 Mar 15 19:14 /lib64/libnvpair.so.1 -> libnvpair.so.1.0.1\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root  84840 Mar 15 19:14 /lib64/libnvpair.so.1.0.1\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root     15 Mar 15 19:14 /lib64/libzfs.so.1 -> libzfs.so.1.0.1\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root 263280 Mar 15 19:14 /lib64/libzfs.so.1.0.1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f9f9bc8cc6f3463183cb8d3dbe27f92d9a37edd0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 310,
        "name": "Richard Yao",
        "email": "ryao@gentoo.org"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-17 02:40:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nChanges in a library's ABI often require changes in the code of various dependencies to support them. On the other hand, failing to require a specific soname often results in incomprehensible runtime failures whenever an ABI change occurs. Requiring that the code be changed should the soname change is preferable to the runtime failures that will result should the ABI change under the binaries.\n\nOn a semi-related note, the use of dlopen() outside of the program loader breaks things that rely on ldd. This generally causes headaches for us downstream. Some examples of headaches that this causes us are as follows:\n\n1. We have a tool called revdep-rebuild that relies on ldd to ensure that all system dynamic link dependencies are satisfied. It will invoke our package manager to rebuild any packages that contain binaries that depend on missing libraries.\n\n2. We have a package manager feature in development called preserved-libs that relies on ldd to detect when updating/removing a package will break a dependency and preserve the library to prevent runtime failures.\n\n3. Our initramfs software has a function called copy_binaries that relies on ldd to copy all dependent libraries into our initramfs. This avoids synchronization issues between our initramfs software and changes in dependent packages that prevent reliable initramfs generation.\n\nThe best thing for us downstream would be to rely on the program loader to dlopen() these libraries. I can see us patching the configure script to provide an option to do that in the future. If/when we do, that patch would be submitted for upstream review. In the interim, it would be desirable to specify the soname version. That will ease the pain associated with an ABI change in the ZFS libraries should one ever occur.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6e3db1deafd606e128d1583e760d856909ff2ae0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 310,
        "name": "Richard Yao",
        "email": "ryao@gentoo.org"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-17 02:46:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTo be clear, I meant reverse-dependencies in my previous comment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "616fa32a365446e05860adb6db0028fb3f63425a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-03-17 03:22:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/4e2834f6-8eaf-11e2-81eb-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  2 tests failed: replay-single, sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "abe6a9f2570b0ac6678ec984e72688973c174ff2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-17 16:42:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe reason we do not use normal dynamic linking for the ZFS libraries is so that we can build with both ldiskfs and ZFS support into the tools without having warnings or errors if users do not install the ZFS libraries. \n\nIn a case such as yours, where you are only building with ZFS support, it seems reasonable to conditionally remove the dlopen() calls and allow the linker to do normal linking so that ldd will show the proper dependencies.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a2f61e43009a8847cc81660874faabe1d34e2e50",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 272,
        "name": "Alexey Shvetsov",
        "email": "alexxy@gentoo.org",
        "username": "alexxy"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-17 17:41:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nDynamic linking via dlopen or any other mechanism can be enabled by configure flag. I can submit another patch that will enabled this behavior.\n\nIn gentoo we can use ldiskfs if it can be used with unpatched mainline kernels (not with havily patched RHEL ones)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d2580cd945d6a4588179a71b2b75a2bc5389faa5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 310,
        "name": "Richard Yao",
        "email": "ryao@gentoo.org"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 12:42:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt would be best to patch lustre to support a configure script option to do dynamic linking through the program loader. We could rely on that to eliminate potential dlopen() issues in Gentoo.\n\nThe concern about calling dlopen() on an unversioned symlink would still be valid, but it would no longer be our problem.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e87133c64025fe65d91c9a61cf6dcfb00a6b9064",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-18 15:37:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
